-- Polecat Code Review — Cell translation of mol-polecat-code-review.formula.toml
-- Sequential workflow: a polecat reviews code and files beads for findings.
-- This is a workflow (not convoy) — steps run in sequence with dependencies.

## polecat-code-review

  input param.scope : str required
  input param.issue : str required
  input param.focus : str default("")
  input param.rig : str required

  -- Reusable persona fragment
  prompt@ polecat-reviewer
    You are a self-cleaning polecat performing a code review.
    Scope: {{param.scope}}
    Tracking issue: {{param.issue}}
    You find and report issues — you do NOT fix them. File beads.
    When done, you self-clean via gt done. Done means gone.

  -- === Step 1: Load context ===

  # load-context : script
    ```sh
    gt prime
    bd prime
    gt hook
    bd show {{param.issue}}
    ls -la {{param.scope}} 2>/dev/null || echo "scope is description, not path"
    git log --oneline -10 -- {{param.scope}} 2>/dev/null || true
    ```
  #/

  -- === Step 2: Survey code structure ===

  # survey-code : llm
    - load-context
    system>
      {{@polecat-reviewer}}
      Your task: survey the code structure before detailed review.
    user>
      Get a high-level understanding of the code at {{param.scope}}.

      Identify:
      - Main types/structs and public functions
      - Dependencies and imports
      - Test coverage (if tests exist)
      - Initial impressions: organization, patterns, risky areas

      Build a mental map. Note areas that need closer inspection.
    context> ?has(param.focus)
      Focus area: {{param.focus}}
    format> survey
      {
        structure_summary: str,
        key_components: [str],
        risky_areas: [str],
        test_coverage: str
      }
  #/

  -- === Step 3: Detailed review ===

  # detailed-review : llm
    - survey-code
    system>
      {{@polecat-reviewer}}
      Your task: systematic detailed code review.
    user>
      Review the code at {{param.scope}} systematically.
      Structure from survey: {{survey-code}}

      Review checklist:
      | Category | Look For |
      |----------|----------|
      | Correctness | Logic errors, off-by-one, nil handling, race conditions |
      | Security | Injection, auth bypass, secrets in code, unsafe operations |
      | Error handling | Swallowed errors, missing checks, unclear error messages |
      | Performance | N+1 queries, unnecessary allocations, blocking calls |
      | Maintainability | Dead code, unclear naming, missing comments |
      | Testing | Untested paths, missing edge cases, flaky tests |

      For each issue note: file, line, category, severity, description, suggested fix.
      Do NOT fix issues yourself — just catalog them.
    context> ?has(param.focus)
      Focus especially on: {{param.focus}}
    format> findings
      {
        issues: [{
          file: str,
          line: number,
          category: "correctness" | "security" | "error_handling" | "performance" | "maintainability" | "testing",
          severity: "P0" | "P1" | "P2" | "P3",
          description: str,
          suggested_fix: str
        }]
      }
  #/

  -- === Step 4: Prioritize findings ===

  # prioritize : llm
    - detailed-review
    system>
      {{@polecat-reviewer}}
      Your task: prioritize and deduplicate findings.
    user>
      Organize these findings by priority:
      {{detailed-review}}

      Priority levels:
      - P0: Security vulnerability, data loss risk — mail Witness immediately
      - P1: Bug affecting users, broken functionality — file as bug, high priority
      - P2: Code quality issue, potential future bug — file as task
      - P3: Improvement opportunity, nice-to-have — file as task, low priority

      Deduplicate overlapping findings. Group by priority then category.
    format> prioritized
      {
        p0: [{ title: str, file: str, description: str }],
        p1: [{ title: str, file: str, description: str }],
        p2: [{ title: str, file: str, description: str }],
        p3: [{ title: str, file: str, description: str }],
        total_count: number
      }

    ```oracle
    json_parse(output);
    keys_present(output, ["p0", "p1", "p2", "p3", "total_count"]);
    assert output.total_count >= 0;
    ```
  #/

  -- === Step 5: File beads ===

  # file-beads : script
    - prioritize
    ```sh
    -- File P0/P1 as bugs, P2/P3 as tasks
    -- This is a template; the polecat fills in from prioritize output
    echo '{{prioritize}}' | jq -r '.p0[] + .p1[] | "bd create --type=bug --priority=1 --title=\"\(.title)\" --description=\"Found in code review of {{param.scope}}. File: \(.file). \(.description)\""' | sh
    echo '{{prioritize}}' | jq -r '.p2[] | "bd create --type=task --priority=2 --title=\"\(.title)\" --description=\"Found in code review of {{param.scope}}. File: \(.file). \(.description)\""' | sh
    echo '{{prioritize}}' | jq -r '.p3[] | "bd create --type=task --priority=3 --title=\"\(.title)\" --description=\"Found in code review of {{param.scope}}. File: \(.file). \(.description)\""' | sh
    ```
  #/

  -- === Step 6: Summarize and update tracking issue ===

  # summarize : llm
    - file-beads
    - prioritize
    system>
      {{@polecat-reviewer}}
      Your task: write a concise review summary for the tracking issue.
    user>
      Write a summary of this code review for the tracking issue.
      Findings: {{prioritize}}

      Include:
      - Scope reviewed
      - Finding counts by priority (P0/P1/P2/P3)
      - Overall assessment (healthy, needs attention, significant issues)
      - List of bead IDs filed
    format> summary
      {
        scope: str,
        p0_count: number,
        p1_count: number,
        p2_count: number,
        p3_count: number,
        assessment: "healthy" | "needs_attention" | "significant_issues",
        bead_ids: [str],
        narrative: str
      }
  #/

  -- === Step 7: Self-clean ===

  # complete : script
    - summarize
    ```sh
    bd update {{param.issue}} --notes "{{summarize.narrative}}"
    bd sync
    gt done
    ```
  #/

  -- Wiring: sequential workflow
  load-context -> survey-code -> detailed-review -> prioritize -> file-beads -> summarize -> complete

  squash> trigger: on_complete template: work include_metrics: true

##/
